00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:37.790
What are some of the best
practices in design?

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:37.990
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:39.060
It's actually a really
good point.

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:42.090
And it's something which we
really try and encourage.

00:04:42.090 --> 00:04:44.640
So what we have in the Design
tab is really a lot of

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:47.760
information around what are
the expectations around

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:50.810
building an app which looks
right on Android.

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:53.140
Now we don't want to get into
a situation where every app

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:54.150
looks the same.

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:55.070
That's boring.

00:04:55.070 --> 00:04:58.020
That's not helping people
create new and really

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.780
interesting experiences.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.950
So what we focus on is providing
a set of guidelines

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:04.940
which will make your
app look at home

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:06.790
within the Android ecosystem.

00:05:06.790 --> 00:05:09.910
So that it will feel as though
it's a part of the system and

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:12.430
integrate well with all the
other apps running there.

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.940
So what we really encourage is
making sure that you don't

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:16.790
break any of those guidelines.

00:05:16.790 --> 00:05:20.320
You don't institute any sort
of user experience actions

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:23.680
which are contrary to
what people expect.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:26.700
For example, if they see tabs on
a screen, they're going to

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:29.040
expect to be able to swipe left
and right using a view

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:31.670
pager to move that content.

00:05:31.670 --> 00:05:34.690
So if you don't do that, then
you introduce this cognitive

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:35.810
dissonance for your users.

00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:36.810
They're going to expect
something to

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:38.330
work, and it doesn't.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:40.060
Suddenly they lose confidence
in their

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:41.390
ability to use your app.

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:43.600
And that makes them less
inclined to use it.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:45.540
So we say, don't break
the guidelines.

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:47.420
Create a consistent
experience.

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:50.200
But use that as a base, and
build on top of that to create

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:51.760
something as unique
as possible.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.300
We really encourage people to
create apps, which are a

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:56.670
unique experience, which
showcase the content which

00:05:56.670 --> 00:05:59.470
that app is delivering in
interesting and innovative

00:05:59.470 --> 00:06:03.110
ways which fit within the
guidelines that we have.

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:05.520
DON DODGE: While we're on the
topic of design, is there a

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:08.730
difference between designing
an app for a mobile device

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:10.370
versus a tablet?

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:11.240
RETO MEIER: I think there is.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:13.040
And it's a really good
way of looking at

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:13.920
it, as well, I think.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:17.030
We try and encourage people
to have, if possible, one

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:20.030
distributable, which will work
on a variety of different

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:21.710
devices and work well.

00:06:21.710 --> 00:06:23.850
And in terms of implementation,
often that's

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:25.780
not too big a challenge.

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:28.370
Where the real challenge comes
in is creating something which

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:32.040
works really well on phones and
tablets and any other kind

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:32.850
of form factor.

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:36.380
And with a lot of different
screen sizes, that can

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:37.690
introduce a challenge
in design.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:40.650
Something which works very well
on a small phone may not

00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:41.930
work as well on a tablet.

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:44.100
And so a big part of what we're
encouraging developers

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:48.210
to do today is take a look at
their app and think about how

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:49.480
will this work well?

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.080
How will this prevent a
better user experience

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.140
on a different device?

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:55.560
Particularly for tablets because
I think a lot of our

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:57.960
developers have come to Android
from that phone

00:06:57.960 --> 00:06:58.820
experience.

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:01.320
And We have a bunch of tools
within the framework to make

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:05.320
sure that many phone apps will
scale up and work reasonably

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:06.830
well on tablets.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:08.260
That's really just
the first step.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.480
I think we're moving now to this
next stage where we want

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:11.620
them to build--

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.940
really design their
apps so that they

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:15.260
work great on tablets.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:18.340
And mint.com is a fantastic
example of this, where they've

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:21.980
looked to see how the
users use our app on

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:23.280
tablets versus phones.

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:27.460
And so they have with one file
which they distribute two

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:29.300
complimentary experiences.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.080
So on the phone, you're using it
to enter your expenses, all

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:35.050
of the things which you're
spending money while

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:36.080
you're on the go.

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:39.270
On the tablet, it's much more
of a browsing interface.

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:39.890
You're sitting down.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:41.950
You're looking to see how
have I spent my money.

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:43.190
It's much more immersive.

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:45.570
It has a much longer
engagement.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:48.340
And they've seen that from using
their analytics, finding

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:51.530
out how are people using the app
on different devices, and

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:54.670
then tailoring the experience
to maximize what people are

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:56.190
already doing on
those devices.

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:58.810
DON DODGE: So the difference
between mobile devices and

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:01.980
tablets, does it have to
do with design and user

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:02.540
experience?

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:05.230
Or are there actually, from an
engineering point of view,

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:09.070
different code that you have
for one versus the other?

00:08:09.070 --> 00:08:10.810
RETO MEIER: Well that's one of
the beauties, I think, of the

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:12.800
way the Android framework
works is that from an

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:14.930
engineering perspective, no.

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:16.340
It's all the same
sort of code.

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:19.260
It's all using the same classes
and methods and

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:20.290
everything else.

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:22.340
You're just having to implement
another design.

00:08:22.340 --> 00:08:25.390
And wherever possible, using
things like fragments, we try

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:27.060
to make that as seamless
as possible.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.270
So you can create different
components, which are just

00:08:29.270 --> 00:08:31.340
effectively arranged
differently.

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:33.150
In a lot of cases, it's
sort of first

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:34.549
past design for tablets.

00:08:34.549 --> 00:08:37.340
It's simply removing a
layer of navigation.

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:39.220
So where on a phone, you
may have a list.

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:40.159
You click an item.

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:41.549
It drills down to
more content.

00:08:41.549 --> 00:08:42.470
You click again.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:43.510
It gives you more content.

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:46.360
On a tablet, particularly in
landscape mode, you have a lot

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:47.410
more screen real estate.

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:49.200
So you can have the
list on the left.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:49.930
You click on it.

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:52.540
It'll have the detail panels
on the right hand side.

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:54.170
So you've got sort of
more on the screen.

00:08:54.170 --> 00:08:57.740
But each of those components
are used in both layouts.

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.230
It's just a matter of laying
them out differently.

00:09:00.230 --> 00:09:02.770
And wherever possible, the
Android framework tries to

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:04.370
make that as simple as it can.

00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:06.750
DON DODGE: So a mobile device
is obviously quite different

00:09:06.750 --> 00:09:07.860
than a tablet.

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:10.890
But even within mobile devices,
there are different

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:13.360
manufacturers, different
screen sizes,

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:14.410
that kind of thing.

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:15.900
How do you deal with that?

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:17.820
RETO MEIER: I think there's two
factors to consider there.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:21.200
And one is we try and think
less about specific form

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.180
factors and more about
screen sizes.

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:26.270
So it's very similar to the way
that web development has

00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:27.320
always worked.

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:30.110
You basically figure out what
layout is going to work and

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:32.100
how small you can make it until
you're going to have to

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:33.850
rethink the user interface
for something

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:35.540
that's easy to use again.

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:38.010
So much of the way we define it
is to say that you need to

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:40.330
have different layouts
for different

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:41.540
minimum screen widths.

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:44.630
And that can take care of a lot
of the variation within

00:09:44.630 --> 00:09:46.860
particular categories.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:50.440
As well as that, we also
like to think about--

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:54.840
I can't remember.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:56.190
Can't remember where I
was going with that.

